1
00:00:52,473 --> 00:00:56,312
It's obviously a
major malfunction.

2
00:01:10,711 --> 00:01:13,392
...their President is a
crook. Well, I'm not a crook.

3
00:01:17,150 --> 00:01:20,791
Robert Kennedy was
shot in that ballroom.

4
00:01:23,229 --> 00:01:25,549
Thank God Almighty,
we are free at last!

5
00:01:25,830 --> 00:01:28,550
A sniper has fired
at President Kennedy.

6
00:01:35,908 --> 00:01:39,908
Or have you ever been a
member of the Communist party?

7
00:01:44,067 --> 00:01:46,067
Hi-yo, Silver!

8
00:01:50,746 --> 00:01:52,425
...1941...

9
00:01:52,987 --> 00:01:56,186
...a date which
will live in infamy.

10
00:02:00,265 --> 00:02:02,257
We bring you the
final edition of

11
00:02:02,258 --> 00:02:04,425
our Maxwell House
Good News of 1939.

12
00:02:04,745 --> 00:02:06,414
Good evening,
Mr. and Mrs. North

13
00:02:06,415 --> 00:02:08,184
America, and all
the ships at sea.

14
00:02:13,103 --> 00:02:17,263
The only thing we have
to fear is fear itself.

15
00:03:21,816 --> 00:03:22,977
CQ...

16
00:03:23,335 --> 00:03:25,255
...this is W-9 GFO.

17
00:03:27,415 --> 00:03:30,655
CQ, this is W-9
GFO here. Come back?

18
00:03:34,495 --> 00:03:35,574
CQ...

19
00:03:35,774 --> 00:03:38,294
...this is W-9 GFO here.

20
00:03:39,135 --> 00:03:40,294
Come back?

21
00:03:44,054 --> 00:03:48,053
CQ, this is W-9 GFO.
Is anybody out there?

22
00:03:49,054 --> 00:03:50,133
Not getting anything.

23
00:03:50,412 --> 00:03:51,852
Small moves, Ellie.

24
00:03:53,413 --> 00:03:54,533
Small moves.

25
00:03:57,053 --> 00:04:00,651
CQ, this is W-9
GFO here. Come back?

26
00:04:01,572 --> 00:04:03,132
Copy, W-9 GFO.

27
00:04:03,331 --> 00:04:05,132
K-4 WLD here.

28
00:04:05,530 --> 00:04:06,891
What do I say?

29
00:04:07,091 --> 00:04:08,490
Just be yourself.

30
00:04:08,971 --> 00:04:11,530
Where are you,
K-4 WLD? Come back?

31
00:04:11,731 --> 00:04:12,970
Pensacola. Over.

32
00:04:13,209 --> 00:04:14,730
Pensacola, where's Pensacola?

33
00:04:15,050 --> 00:04:16,449
I'll give you a hint.

34
00:04:17,131 --> 00:04:18,210
Orange juice.

35
00:04:20,929 --> 00:04:24,408
Copy that, K-4 WLD. How's the
weather down there in Florida?

36
00:04:25,609 --> 00:04:27,488
Pensacola, Florida.

37
00:04:28,129 --> 00:04:29,889
I have to tell you, Sparks.

38
00:04:30,728 --> 00:04:32,929
1,116 miles.

39
00:04:34,408 --> 00:04:35,487
Pretty good.

40
00:04:35,768 --> 00:04:37,247
That's the farthest yet.

41
00:04:49,566 --> 00:04:51,365
Can we hear all
the way to New York?

42
00:04:51,606 --> 00:04:52,766
Sure.

43
00:04:54,085 --> 00:04:56,004
Can we hear all the
way to California?

44
00:04:56,245 --> 00:04:57,886
I don't see why not.

45
00:04:58,605 --> 00:05:00,524
Can we hear all
the way to Alaska?

46
00:05:00,885 --> 00:05:02,165
On a really clear day.

47
00:05:02,364 --> 00:05:04,284
Can we hear all
the way to China?

48
00:05:05,284 --> 00:05:07,644
On a really, really clear day.

49
00:05:09,404 --> 00:05:11,523
Could we talk to the moon?

50
00:05:12,084 --> 00:05:14,843
If it's a big enough
radio, I don't see why not.

51
00:05:15,482 --> 00:05:17,402
Could we talk to Jupiter?

52
00:05:17,602 --> 00:05:20,002
Or what's the one after that?

53
00:05:20,441 --> 00:05:21,683
Don't tell me.

54
00:05:24,002 --> 00:05:25,282
I'll give you a hint.

55
00:05:25,722 --> 00:05:26,842
Hula-Hoops.

56
00:05:27,042 --> 00:05:28,962
Saturn! Could we
talk to Saturn?

57
00:05:34,400 --> 00:05:36,802
Dad, could we talk to Mom?

58
00:05:42,201 --> 00:05:45,320
I don't think even the biggest
radio could reach that far.

59
00:05:50,120 --> 00:05:51,878
All right, no more stalling.

60
00:05:56,638 --> 00:05:58,038
Pensacola!

61
00:06:05,557 --> 00:06:06,758
That's a beauty.

62
00:06:08,157 --> 00:06:09,557
Now get some sleep.

63
00:06:17,557 --> 00:06:18,796
Hey, Dad?

64
00:06:19,836 --> 00:06:22,355
Do you think there's
people on other planets?

65
00:06:22,515 --> 00:06:24,156
I don't know, Sparks.

66
00:06:25,595 --> 00:06:27,156
But I guess I'd say...

67
00:06:27,674 --> 00:06:29,434
...if it is just us...

68
00:06:30,954 --> 00:06:33,115
...it seems like an
awful waste of space.

69
00:06:51,952 --> 00:06:54,232
CQ, this is W-9 GFO.

70
00:06:54,391 --> 00:06:56,913
Repeat. This is
W-9 GFO. Come back?

71
00:07:04,630 --> 00:07:06,551
I'm going to need
a bigger antenna.

72
00:07:32,467 --> 00:07:34,027
What do you think, Doc Arroway?

73
00:07:34,228 --> 00:07:35,666
Isn't she a beauty?

74
00:07:39,626 --> 00:07:40,707
It'll do.

75
00:07:40,906 --> 00:07:42,786
The village is five miles away.

76
00:07:42,986 --> 00:07:45,175
There's a general
store in the cantina.

77
00:07:45,175 --> 00:07:47,306
They can order
anything from San Juan.

78
00:07:47,505 --> 00:07:48,945
When can I get dish time?

79
00:07:49,105 --> 00:07:50,596
Dr. Clark said you couldn't

80
00:07:50,597 --> 00:07:52,584
wait. Your first
shift is tonight.

81
00:08:46,380 --> 00:08:47,498
Go back.

82
00:08:49,380 --> 00:08:51,979
Try back a little bit.
You had something there.

83
00:08:53,259 --> 00:08:54,219
There!

84
00:08:54,537 --> 00:08:55,337
- Right there?

85
00:08:55,337 --> 00:08:57,618
- You hear it? Right
there, that's it.

86
00:08:57,899 --> 00:09:01,418
All right, 1221.46. That's
well within the L-band.

87
00:09:01,737 --> 00:09:02,656
Check off-axis.

88
00:09:03,657 --> 00:09:04,736
On it.

89
00:09:06,377 --> 00:09:07,816
It's not in the neighborhood.

90
00:09:16,296 --> 00:09:18,216
Here it is. J-1741...

91
00:09:18,496 --> 00:09:20,095
...+ 2748.

92
00:09:20,294 --> 00:09:23,335
Catalogued November
4, 1982. Pulsar.

93
00:09:25,894 --> 00:09:28,894
Must've been the glitch in
the timing's what threw me.

94
00:09:29,135 --> 00:09:30,695
Must've been a starquake.

95
00:09:32,014 --> 00:09:33,600
I think it's great that you

96
00:09:33,601 --> 00:09:35,773
listen. Most don't
do that anymore.

97
00:09:35,973 --> 00:09:38,654
It's just an old habit.
It makes it feel more real.

98
00:09:38,853 --> 00:09:39,733
Ellie.

99
00:09:39,932 --> 00:09:41,053
Kent Clark.

100
00:09:43,812 --> 00:09:45,374
They said you'd been...

101
00:09:45,572 --> 00:09:47,932
...up at Owen's Valley
working under Drumlin.

102
00:09:48,093 --> 00:09:49,412
How'd you like him?

103
00:09:52,492 --> 00:09:54,386
That much? About
what I'd expect

104
00:09:54,387 --> 00:09:56,452
after what he had
to say about you.

105
00:09:56,771 --> 00:09:58,331
And what was that?

106
00:09:58,850 --> 00:10:00,290
That you are brilliant...

107
00:10:00,570 --> 00:10:01,730
...driven...

108
00:10:02,051 --> 00:10:03,491
...a major pain in the ass...

109
00:10:03,810 --> 00:10:05,127
...and obsessed with a field of

110
00:10:05,128 --> 00:10:06,570
study he considers
tantamount...

111
00:10:06,729 --> 00:10:08,089
...to professional suicide.

112
00:10:08,769 --> 00:10:09,729
Anything else?

113
00:10:09,930 --> 00:10:11,609
Those were the highlights.

114
00:10:12,129 --> 00:10:14,489
Davio, Dr. Vernon. Dr. Arroway.

115
00:10:15,968 --> 00:10:18,131
Believe you've already
met our tireless

116
00:10:18,132 --> 00:10:19,968
research assistant,
Mr. Fisher...

117
00:10:20,647 --> 00:10:22,847
...as well as his cologne.

118
00:10:23,488 --> 00:10:25,727
Brook's looking at
the black hole in M-87.

119
00:10:25,888 --> 00:10:29,568
Eli's studying Markarian
541, a major gamma ray source.

120
00:10:29,887 --> 00:10:31,867
Dr. Arroway will
be spending her

121
00:10:31,868 --> 00:10:34,327
precious telescope
time listening for...

122
00:10:35,046 --> 00:10:36,927
...listening for...

123
00:10:37,126 --> 00:10:38,567
Little green men.

124
00:10:46,285 --> 00:10:47,565
One down...

125
00:10:48,084 --> 00:10:49,724
...a couple billion to go.

126
00:11:05,843 --> 00:11:07,604
Arecibo, right?

127
00:11:08,722 --> 00:11:09,843
Does it show?

128
00:11:11,882 --> 00:11:13,002
Cracker Jack?

129
00:11:13,203 --> 00:11:13,963
No, thanks.

130
00:11:14,162 --> 00:11:15,403
Mind if I sit down?

131
00:11:17,242 --> 00:11:21,000
I hear the locals, they
call it "El Radar. "

132
00:11:21,202 --> 00:11:23,720
Convinced it has some
dark military purpose.

133
00:11:24,122 --> 00:11:25,481
I think we're harmless.

134
00:11:26,879 --> 00:11:28,000
Palmer Joss.

135
00:11:28,760 --> 00:11:31,160
- Ellie Arroway.
- Nice to meet you, Ellie.

136
00:11:32,280 --> 00:11:34,958
What are you studying up there?

137
00:11:36,758 --> 00:11:38,000
The usual.

138
00:11:38,200 --> 00:11:41,838
Nebulae, quasars,
pulsars, stuff like that.

139
00:11:42,238 --> 00:11:43,638
What are you writing?

140
00:11:43,958 --> 00:11:46,039
The usual. Nouns, adverbs...

141
00:11:46,239 --> 00:11:47,718
...adjective here and there.

142
00:11:49,398 --> 00:11:50,877
I work on a project, SETI.

143
00:11:51,638 --> 00:11:53,559
Search for Extraterrestrial
Intelligence?

144
00:11:55,638 --> 00:11:57,237
That is out there!

145
00:11:58,437 --> 00:12:00,637
Are you a student or something?

146
00:12:01,116 --> 00:12:03,157
I'm a writer. I'm
writing a book.

147
00:12:03,677 --> 00:12:05,672
I'm here doing
research about how

148
00:12:05,673 --> 00:12:08,075
technology affects
Third World cultures.

149
00:12:08,315 --> 00:12:10,836
I'm also looking for
this guy, David Drumlin.

150
00:12:11,156 --> 00:12:13,145
He's head of the
National Science

151
00:12:13,146 --> 00:12:15,075
Foundation. I
want an interview.

152
00:12:16,274 --> 00:12:17,955
I take it you know him?

153
00:12:19,315 --> 00:12:20,754
You could say that.

154
00:12:22,034 --> 00:12:23,474
SETI.

155
00:12:23,674 --> 00:12:25,275
That's fringe!

156
00:12:25,675 --> 00:12:27,878
I've crossed paths
with him. Something

157
00:12:27,879 --> 00:12:29,913
like that must
really chap his ass.

158
00:12:32,752 --> 00:12:33,753
Compass.

159
00:12:35,674 --> 00:12:36,913
That's for you.

160
00:12:41,593 --> 00:12:42,992
You better keep this.

161
00:12:44,151 --> 00:12:45,751
Might save your life someday.

162
00:12:50,352 --> 00:12:51,871
Have dinner with me tonight?

163
00:12:54,711 --> 00:12:57,870
I don't make a good research
subject. I'm not quotable.

164
00:12:58,191 --> 00:13:00,391
No quotes. Scout's honor.

165
00:13:00,790 --> 00:13:02,030
Good meal, good company.

166
00:13:02,868 --> 00:13:04,109
I've got to go.

167
00:13:12,907 --> 00:13:14,629
Drumlin's coming in Tuesday.

168
00:13:23,187 --> 00:13:26,387
Now I remember why
I took that desk job.

169
00:13:27,866 --> 00:13:29,787
Dr. Drumlin, how are you?

170
00:13:31,306 --> 00:13:32,786
Glad you could make it.

171
00:13:33,906 --> 00:13:36,746
If I'd known it took 3 planes,
I might've reconsidered.

172
00:13:36,945 --> 00:13:38,226
How is that new office?

173
00:13:38,426 --> 00:13:40,579
Still settling in.
They already want

174
00:13:40,580 --> 00:13:42,905
to give half my
budget to the Pentagon.

175
00:13:43,625 --> 00:13:45,905
Still waiting for E.T. to call?

176
00:13:47,825 --> 00:13:49,384
Good to see you too!

177
00:13:49,904 --> 00:13:50,864
Asshole!

178
00:13:51,103 --> 00:13:53,223
Looks like it's going
to be a long night.

179
00:13:53,425 --> 00:13:55,603
Science must be
accountable to the

180
00:13:55,604 --> 00:13:57,903
people paying for
it, the taxpayers.

181
00:13:58,063 --> 00:14:01,222
We must stop wasting money on
pie-in-the-sky abstractions...

182
00:14:01,384 --> 00:14:04,102
...and spend it on
practical, measurable ways...

183
00:14:04,263 --> 00:14:06,862
...to improve the lives of
the people who are paying.

184
00:14:07,022 --> 00:14:10,102
Not unlike my L-band,
globular clusters work.

185
00:14:10,343 --> 00:14:13,182
You want to do away with
all pure research now?

186
00:14:13,381 --> 00:14:16,622
What's wrong with science being
practical? Even profitable?

187
00:14:16,821 --> 00:14:18,861
Nothing, as long
as your motive...

188
00:14:19,141 --> 00:14:20,972
...is the search
for truth. Which

189
00:14:20,973 --> 00:14:22,860
is what the pursuit
of science is.

190
00:14:25,381 --> 00:14:27,661
That's an interesting
position from a man...

191
00:14:27,860 --> 00:14:30,379
...on a crusade against
the evils of technology...

192
00:14:30,660 --> 00:14:31,740
...Father Joss.

193
00:14:32,379 --> 00:14:35,580
I'm not against technology,
Doctor. I'm against...

194
00:14:35,780 --> 00:14:38,898
...the men who deify it at
the expense of human truth.

195
00:14:42,819 --> 00:14:46,057
Kent, I need to have a word
with you. Over here, please.

196
00:14:51,497 --> 00:14:54,498
You think that hurt my
chances with that interview?

197
00:14:55,096 --> 00:14:56,456
You're a priest?

198
00:14:58,297 --> 00:14:59,417
Not really.

199
00:15:00,135 --> 00:15:02,776
I got my Masters in Divinity...

200
00:15:03,256 --> 00:15:06,536
...then left the seminary to
do secular humanitarian work...

201
00:15:06,776 --> 00:15:09,095
...coordinating
Third World churches.

202
00:15:09,816 --> 00:15:11,775
I couldn't live with
the celibacy thing.

203
00:15:16,214 --> 00:15:18,174
You could call me
a man of the cloth...

204
00:15:19,414 --> 00:15:20,894
...without the cloth.

205
00:15:24,133 --> 00:15:25,653
You want to get out of here?

206
00:15:27,573 --> 00:15:29,414
You see that large W-shaped

207
00:15:29,415 --> 00:15:32,213
constellation there?
That's Cassiopeia.

208
00:15:32,613 --> 00:15:36,853
And Cassiopeia A gives off
a whole lot of radio signals.

209
00:15:37,171 --> 00:15:38,772
I listen to them a lot.

210
00:15:39,012 --> 00:15:41,212
It's a remnant of a supernova.

211
00:15:42,171 --> 00:15:44,691
When did you know you
wanted to be an astronomer?

212
00:15:46,971 --> 00:15:49,131
When I was about
eight years old...

213
00:15:49,331 --> 00:15:51,659
...watching the
sunset, I asked Dad,

214
00:15:51,660 --> 00:15:54,050
"What's that bright
star over there?"

215
00:15:57,370 --> 00:16:00,369
He said that it wasn't
a star. It was...

216
00:16:02,210 --> 00:16:04,529
...a whole planet
called Venus...

217
00:16:08,008 --> 00:16:11,088
...which should
be over there soon.

218
00:16:12,048 --> 00:16:14,327
He said, "You know why
they called it Venus?

219
00:16:14,768 --> 00:16:17,848
Because they thought it was
so beautiful and glowing.

220
00:16:18,127 --> 00:16:19,607
But they didn't know...

221
00:16:20,287 --> 00:16:22,807
...that it's filled with...

222
00:16:24,006 --> 00:16:27,246
...deadly gases and
sulfuric acid rain. "

223
00:16:28,527 --> 00:16:31,885
Wow, I thought, "This
is it! I'm hooked!"

224
00:16:34,046 --> 00:16:37,525
There are four hundred
billion stars out there...

225
00:16:37,805 --> 00:16:39,564
...just in our galaxy alone.

226
00:16:40,524 --> 00:16:44,044
If only one out of a million
of those had planets...

227
00:16:44,445 --> 00:16:47,444
...if just one out of a
million of those had life...

228
00:16:47,604 --> 00:16:49,692
...and if just one
out of a million

229
00:16:49,693 --> 00:16:51,604
of those had
intelligent life...

230
00:16:52,363 --> 00:16:54,771
...there would be
literally millions

231
00:16:54,772 --> 00:16:56,722
of civilizations out there...

232
00:16:58,563 --> 00:17:00,042
If there wasn't...

233
00:17:00,923 --> 00:17:03,003
...it'd be an awful
waste of space.

234
00:17:08,682 --> 00:17:09,842
Amen.

235
00:17:18,400 --> 00:17:22,200
So I was lying there,
just looking at the sky.

236
00:17:25,960 --> 00:17:28,839
And then I felt
something. I don't know.

237
00:17:30,119 --> 00:17:32,679
All I know is that
I wasn't alone.

238
00:17:33,040 --> 00:17:37,077
For the first time in my life
I wasn't scared of nothing...

239
00:17:37,999 --> 00:17:39,518
...not even dying.

240
00:17:44,918 --> 00:17:46,637
It was God.

241
00:17:49,277 --> 00:17:51,156
And there's no chance that...

242
00:17:51,637 --> 00:17:53,669
...you had this
experience because

243
00:17:53,670 --> 00:17:55,756
some part of you
needed to have it?

244
00:17:56,916 --> 00:18:00,235
I'm a reasonably
intelligent guy, but this...

245
00:18:02,996 --> 00:18:06,514
My intellect couldn't
even touch this.

246
00:18:07,036 --> 00:18:07,955
No.

247
00:18:10,355 --> 00:18:12,875
I've been to Sunday
school a few times.

248
00:18:14,995 --> 00:18:15,834
And?

249
00:18:16,034 --> 00:18:20,393
I kept asking all these really
annoying questions like...

250
00:18:21,274 --> 00:18:23,593
..."Where did Mrs.
Cain come from?"

251
00:18:25,472 --> 00:18:27,713
And pretty soon
they asked my dad...

252
00:18:27,874 --> 00:18:30,552
...if he wouldn't mind
keeping me home from now on.

253
00:18:30,753 --> 00:18:32,031
Your dad...

254
00:18:33,633 --> 00:18:35,152
Is it this guy?

255
00:18:35,352 --> 00:18:36,471
Yeah.

256
00:18:38,511 --> 00:18:40,431
You're close to
him, aren't you?

257
00:18:41,752 --> 00:18:44,711
I was. He died when
I was nine years old.

258
00:18:46,831 --> 00:18:48,710
I never got to know my mother.

259
00:18:50,310 --> 00:18:51,550
I'm sorry.

260
00:18:55,909 --> 00:18:57,750
That's got to be tough.

261
00:19:02,030 --> 00:19:03,588
Being alone.

262
00:19:12,107 --> 00:19:13,306
What do you say...

263
00:19:13,547 --> 00:19:16,868
...we pack a picnic tomorrow
and hike up to Mount Arecibo?

264
00:19:17,706 --> 00:19:20,586
I don't think I can.
I've got to work.

265
00:19:22,306 --> 00:19:25,586
How about dinner tomorrow
night? I know a great dive.

266
00:19:25,986 --> 00:19:27,465
No, I don't think so.

267
00:19:31,947 --> 00:19:34,024
Ellie, did I miss something?

268
00:19:36,104 --> 00:19:37,185
No.

269
00:19:37,384 --> 00:19:39,145
Shit, I'm late!

270
00:19:40,105 --> 00:19:42,864
I told Kent that I'd
be there at 10:30.

271
00:19:45,423 --> 00:19:47,144
I'm not trying to push you.

272
00:19:47,343 --> 00:19:49,504
I've wanted to look at
this sector for weeks.

273
00:19:49,703 --> 00:19:51,302
Just hang out...

274
00:19:51,623 --> 00:19:54,463
...and sleep in. There's
food in the fridge.

275
00:19:56,103 --> 00:19:57,143
How can I reach you?

276
00:19:58,701 --> 00:20:00,862
Just leave your
number. I'll call you.

277
00:20:21,779 --> 00:20:22,698
Dad!

278
00:20:24,659 --> 00:20:27,099
It's starting, you're
going to miss it!

279
00:20:30,538 --> 00:20:32,658
Dad, there's another
one! Hurry up!

280
00:20:32,818 --> 00:20:35,098
